With the older clustering Confluence versions, it was necessary to store attachments and plugins into the database.

Is there any reason why plugins can't be moved to disk storage? It would make upgrades so much easier for users. If a plugin is halting Confluence from starting up during an upgrade, you can just move it off the filesystem instead of going into the database and recalling cryptic SQL to disable them. You can also "pre-upgrade" the plugins with the latest versions before starting Confluence as well on the filesystem.

Also consider when users set up testing environments. You can just zip up the plugins directory to production to ensure everything is exactly the same.

